Agglomerative and Divisive

Dendogram

A diagram which shows where the clusters are. A visual representation of how the data can be clustered. Gives you the options of how many clusters you can have. Longest bar indicates biggest difference

Distance Measures

The choice of distance measures will depend on the dataset and context. Classical - geometrical difference between points on a graph. e.g. Euclydian distance Correlation - how correlated are two data points.

Heirarchical clustering in R

edu_data_scale <- edu_data %>%
              janitor::clean_names() %>%
              rename(state = x1) %>%
              mutate_if(is.numeric, scale)
edu_data_scale
edu_data_scale %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  pivot_longer(-state, 
               names_to = "type", 
               values_to = "value") %>% #convert data to long format
  group_by(type)%>%
  summarise(mean = round(mean(value)), 
            sd = sd(value))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Calculate correlation distances

library(corrplot)
# can't plot categories on a correlation plot (needs numbers only)
edu_numeric <- edu_data_scale %>%
  select(-state)
# create a correlation plot
corrplot(cor(edu_numeric), method = "number", type = "lower")

Calculate distances

# take only high school
diss_matrix <- edu_data %>%
    column_to_rownames("X1") %>%
              select(high_school) %>%
              dist(method = "euclidean") 
fviz_dist(diss_matrix)

Explore different linkage methods

# find clusters that minimise variance
alt_clusters <- diss_matrix %>% 
  hclust(method = "ward.D2")

# get dendogram complete linkage
clustering_dendogram <- clusters_wo_scale %>% 
  as.dendrogram() %>% 
  dendextend::set("labels_cex", 0.5)

# dendogram variance method
alt_clustering_dendogram <- alt_clusters %>% 
  as.dendrogram() %>% 
  dendextend::set("labels_cex", 0.5)

Task

Spend some time carrying out cluster analysis for your other variables community_college, college, and grad_school. What do you find for each variable? How many clusters do you choose, and why? What are your interpretations from your analysis? What happens if you include all your data and perform clustering? (i.e. do not subset the data as we did in one of our first steps). For this, you have moved from predicting a specific variable to predicting something you might denoted as “overall education rates”. Do you get different results when the clustering takes into account all your data at once for each state? How would you interpret your results?
